{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4b5d8b35-b0f0-4dea-beac-186e32b0094b","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\nHere's the difference:\n\n| Command | What it does |\n|---------|--------------|\n| `dotnet workload update` | Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads for your current SDK band. |\n| `dotnet workload repair` | **Reinstalls** the already-installed workload versions — fixes corruption but doesn't upgrade anything. |\n\nSince you updated the SDK and the workloads are now *out of date* (not corrupted), `workload update` will pull in the MAUI workload versions that match your new SDK. After that, your project should build again.\n\nIf the build still fails after updating, you can also try:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload restore   # installs any workloads required by your project file\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"464c1270-f481-47dd-aa5e-f69a3a084d53","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix a .NET MAUI build issue after an SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to look at any files or run any commands.\n\nLet me answer concisely:\n\n- `dotnet workload update` — updates all installed workloads to the latest available versions for your SDK band. This is what you want after an SDK update, as it pulls in workload versions compatible with your new SDK.\n- `dotnet workload repair` — reinstalls all installed workloads. It fixes corrupted installations but doesn't update to newer versions.\n\n\n- Since the issue stems from workloads being out of sync with the new SDK, `dotnet workload update` is the right command to run.","outputTokens":378,"requestId":"A85B:1D8045:657079:74F4A4:69FBE1C9"},"id":"0696381f-cbd6-4d9e-9164-2f3bee0f17c3","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:50:29.882Z","parentId":"54be64e4-cbb5-4b82-a785-d51630214b2d"}
